{
  "text": "The last interglacial period on Oahu, in the Hawaiian Islands (Fig. 1b) , is recorded by the Waimanalo Formation, which consists of emergent, growth-position coral reefs and coral-bearing marine conglomerate. Elevations of both the reef facies and conglomerate facies on Oahu are usually 1 to 6 m above modern sea level, but shallow-marine or beach sediments are found as high as 13 m above sea level at two localities (Mokapu Point and Kahe Point). Oahu has probably experienced minor uplift due to lithospheric flexure from subsidence of the \"Big Island\" of Hawaii . Over the timescale considered here, however, Oahu can be considered to be relatively stable. An earlier study reported acceptable U-series ages of corals from the Waimanalo Formation that range from 130,000 \u00b1 2500 to 110,500 \u00b1 3800 yr B.P., with many ages between 129,000 and 118,000 yr B.P. (Fig. 2b) . New, higher precision ages of different coral samples from the same localities on Oahu show a somewhat more restricted range of acceptable ages, from 127,500 \u00b1 800 to 115,800 \u00b1 600 yr B.P. [CITATION_1] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
